Every year, I wish I could somehow runaway from my birthday.

January 19 always comes way too quickly. At some point in my life, celebrating my birthday became a huge stressor for me. 

The idea of people coming together for lil ol me makes me so uncomfortable lol. I start spiraling wondering if everyone will get along, worried if everyone’s having a good time, on the one day out of the year that it’s actually supposed to be about me 😅

I’m turning 28 and I’m thankful to have gotten this far, but one day I hope to feel more joy on my birthday than relief the day after.

Get ready with me while I have a verbal brain dump about aging. Can you relate?

Aging is a privilege! We aren’t meant to look the same forever, It’s just crazy how we can wake up one day, look in the mirror and feel like a stranger. It’s an out of body experience.

Whenever I look at old photos of myself (the ones that weren’t botched with Facetune anyway🤣) I know that i don’t look like that anymore and I’m okay with it! But I know that what I see in those photos now isn’t how I saw myself in the moment?

It goes beyond weight gain, second puberty, etc. i literally just woke up one day, looked in the mirror and was confused lol. I’m used to doing my makeup a certain way but i just can’t put a finger on how my face has changed 🙃

I guess in a way, I’m kind of excited to get to know my face again lol.

Join me on the chaotic rollercoaster of straightening my hair for the first time in almost a decade!

Just a verbal brain dump of everything I was feeling. I never thought I'd straighten my hair again because of all the mixed feelings I've had about it throughout my natural hair journey.

Throughout my childhood I did it because I thought it was the only way to be presentable but in my teens I did it out of self hatred. Looking my 'best' wasn't tied to my curly hair, only to white, American proximity. Looking back it makes me sad, but I'm also proud of how far I've come.

It wasn't until my early 20's when my hair was fried beyond repair at a salon, that I started to realize my unhealthy attachment to my hair. Despite being natural since 2011 I still had and HAVE, some healing to do. 

That said, I definitely won't be waiting another 8 years to straighten my hair lol. I'm excited to switch it up more often, but I'm even more excited for the day I'm completely detached from the emotional roller coaster of manipulating my hair texture.
